
URL reference: https://itnext.io/how-do-kubernetes-user-namespaces-work-84b9c02cd5f9?gi=86c38f73a674
DateReviewed: 2026-02-01
Description: Today's article dives into user namespaces which are enabled by default as of v1.33. We dive right in, and they explain that user namespaces add a layer of security and reduce the blast radius if something goes wrong. Next, we move into some of the details - first, the feature is Linux only, and your env has to be set up right to use them. The author mentions a specific OS/kernel/K8s server and containerd versions he got it working with. To illustrate, they look at a conventional pod, and show the underlying Linux process, noting it runs as root. They toggle a swtich on, and look again -- this time, it is running as a non root user with a large user ID. They then dive into userID mapping; again, they start with a non-mapped pod, which is actually just a 1-1 mapping that matches the node. For our user namespace, the map is from root to a large uid, but only for 65k entries, which is configurable. We then explore an example, which they show us the passwd file for the node, and then execute a command on the pod, then check on the node who the owner of the process is. The result is that the owner is the map start value plus the uid of the user; pretty neat. To finish up, they mention that you have to test to ensure that user namespaces work - the toggle will silently fail but still create the pod, so you won't get the benefits.
BottomLine: Walkthrough of how User Namepaces work in Kubernetes
